Nature well-being has been recently in jeopardy requiring urgent attention (Antonelli et al., 2019; Liotta et al., 2020; 
                     Sharifi et al., 2021; Kato-Huerta and Geneletti, 2022). Anthropogenic impacts like global warming and biodiversity loss have recently accelerated at an unprecedented rate (Turnhout et al., 2013; Johnson et al., 2017; Blackmore and Oldfield, 2017) that decreased human well-being (Kuzevanov and Sizykh, 2006) . It is projected 40% of plant species are endangered with extinction (Antonelli et al., 2019). Besides, 75% of land-based environment and around 66% of marine environment have been changed by human impact (United Nations, 2022; 
                     Ichii et al., 2019). Future climate impact (Minx et al., 2017) and biodiversity emergency projections are dire (Hooper et al., 2012; Johnson et al., 2017). Here, botanical gardens (BGs) are at the forefront to overcome global crises by their environmental works and technical expertise.

The role of BGs is important concerning social justice and environmental justice that are related to social and spatial inclusion. Social and environmental responsibility is interconnected that contribute to human well-being (Kumar and Reddy, 2007; 
                     Breslow et al., 2016) and the work of BGs demonstrate this (Kuzevanov and Sizykh, 2006; Lynch, 2015). In order to broaden their audiences, BGs work with communities and funding bodies.
                        Many gardens are publicly funded organisations means that they are increasingly required to be accountable to that public, encouraging site development and broader audience engagement. In many cases, to get funding to survive and thrive, they need to demonstrate evidence for such actions (Dodd and Jones, 2010; 5–6).
